1. Calculate the number of students in the three groups: Group (12,14]: 500×0.10=50 students, Group (14,16]: 500×0.04=20 students, Group (16,18]: 500×0.01=10 students;
2. Select 10 students by stratified sampling, calculate the number of students selected from Group (14,16]: $ rac{20}{50+20+10}×10=2$ students, and a total of 8 students are selected from the other two groups;
3. Determine the possible values of X are 0,1,2;
4. Calculate the probability of each value: $P(X=0)= rac{C_{8}^{3}}{C_{10}^{3}}= rac{56}{120}= rac{7}{15}$, $P(X=1)= rac{C_{2}^{1}C_{8}^{2}}{C_{10}^{3}}= rac{56}{120}= rac{7}{15}$, $P(X=2)= rac{C_{2}^{2}C_{8}^{1}}{C_{10}^{3}}= rac{8}{120}= rac{1}{15}$;
5. List the probability distribution of X showing the values and the corresponding probabilities in the form of a table.

1. Let $h(x)=f'(x)=\sin x + x\cos x$, find the derivative of $h(x)$ to get $h'(x)=2\cos x - x\sin x$;
2. Analyze the sign of $h'(x)$ when $x\in( rac{\pi}{2},\pi)$: $\cos x<0$, $\sin x>0$ and $x>0$ in this interval, so $h'(x)=2\cos x - x\sin x<0$, that is, $h(x)$ is monotonically decreasing on $( rac{\pi}{2},\pi)$;
3. Calculate the value of the derivative function at the endpoints of the interval: $f'( rac{\pi}{2})=\sin rac{\pi}{2}+ rac{\pi}{2}\cos rac{\pi}{2}=1>0$, $f'(\pi)=\sin\pi+\pi\cos\pi=-\pi<0$;
4. According to the Zero Existence Theorem, the monotonically decreasing function $h(x)$ has exactly one zero point $x_0$ in $( rac{\pi}{2},\pi)$, that is, $f'(x_0)=0$;
5. Analyze the extreme point: when $x\in( rac{\pi}{2},x_0)$, $f'(x)>0$ and $f(x)$ is monotonically increasing; when $x\in(x_0,\pi)$, $f'(x)<0$ and $f(x)$ is monotonically decreasing, so $x_0$ is the only extreme point of $f(x)$ in $( rac{\pi}{2},\pi)$.

1. From (I) and (II), it is known that $f(x)$ is monotonically increasing in $(1,x_0)$ and monotonically decreasing in $(x_0,\pi)$, where $x_0\in( rac{\pi}{2},\pi)$;
2. Analyze the value of $f(x)$ on $(1,\pi]$: $f(1)=\sin1>0$, $f(\pi)=\pi\sin\pi=0$, so when $x\in(1,\pi]$, $f(x)\geq0$, that is, $f(x)+1\geq1$;
3. Analyze the value of the denominator $\ln x$ on $(1,\pi]$: $\ln x$ is monotonically increasing in this interval, so $0<\ln x\leq\ln\pi$;
4. Analyze the minimum value of $g(x)$: $f(x)+1$ first increases and then decreases on $(1,\pi]$, $\ln x$ is monotonically increasing, when $x=\pi$, $f(x)+1=1$, $\ln x=\ln\pi$, at this time $g(x)= rac{1}{\ln\pi}$, which is the minimum value combined with the monotonicity of the function.

