1. Substitute $a_n$, $a_{n+1}$, $a_{n+2}$ into Condition ③ of property P(m): $[5+4×(- rac{1}{2})^n]+[5+4×(- rac{1}{2})^{n+1}]=m[5+4×(- rac{1}{2})^{n+2}]$;
2. Simplify the left side to get $10+2×(- rac{1}{2})^n$, and simplify the right side to get $m[5+(- rac{1}{2})^n]$;
3. Get $m=2$ by comparing the coefficients on both sides of the equation;
4. Analyze the value range of $a_n$: $(- rac{1}{2})^n\in(- rac{1}{2}, rac{1}{4}]$, so $a_n<5+4× rac{1}{2}=7$, and T=6 can be taken (any positive number T≥6 is acceptable).

1. If the sequence has property P(1), then Condition ③ is $a_n+a_{n+1}=a_{n+2}(n=1,2,...)$;
2. Get $a_{n+2}=a_n+a_{n+1}>a_{n+1}$ from $a_n>0$, that is, the sequence $\{a_n\}$ is monotonically increasing from the third term;
3. Deduce that $a_{n+3}>n a_2+a_3$, combined with Condition ② of property P(m), there exists T>0 such that $a_n≤T$;
4. When $n> rac{T-a_3}{a_2}$, $a_{n+3}>T$, which contradicts Condition ②, so the sequence does not exist.

1. It is known from (II) that $m≠1$, discuss by cases: 
Case 1: $m=2$, the recurrence formula is $a_n+a_{n+1}=2a_{n+2}$, which can be transformed into $a_{n+2}-a_{n+1}=- rac{1}{2}(a_{n+1}-a_n)$, then $|a_{n+2}-a_{n+1}|= rac{1}{2^n}|a_2-a_1|$; since all terms of the sequence are positive integers, $a_n=c$ holds for all n only when $a_2=a_1=c$ (c is a positive integer), which satisfies all conditions of property P(2);
Case 2: $m≥3$, let $b_n=max\{a_n,a_{n+1}\}$, then $a_{n+2}= rac{1}{m}(a_n+a_{n+1})<b_n$, similarly $a_{n+3}<b_n$, so $b_{n+2}≤b_n-1$, and it is deduced that $b_{2n+1}≤b_1-n$; when $n≥b_1$, $b_{2n+1}≤0$, which contradicts that $a_n$ is a positive integer, so $m≥3$ is not valid;
2. In conclusion, the general term formula of the sequence $\{a_n\}$ is the constant sequence $a_n=c$ (c is a positive integer).
